WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:17.000
What was your awareness or impression of race growing up in Hawaii at that time?

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:25.000
I really didn't have any idea at all because I went to school with different nationalities, Japanese, Filipino, Chinese.

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:34.000
I think there was only one Negro family in the whole section of what they didn't have any children.

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:43.000
It wasn't really until I went to New York that I found out about the racial problem.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:47.000
I was going to ask, what was it like to go to New York after it was great?

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:48.000
I loved it.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:51.000
My father was still trying to break up my...

00:00:51.000 --> 00:01:06.000
But it's funny the way things are because I went to New York and got into a Columbia University for a standographic session.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:10.000
And by that time I got a job in my father's house.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:16.000
Well, if you love New York you've got to support yourself. We've got younger brothers that said, fine.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:23.000
I went to the employment office and they sent me to the NAACP office, the National Office in New York.

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:33.000
And I think there was a blessing really because I learned about the racial problems only then did I learn about the racial problems.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:39.000
And I worked for the secretary, for the director of branches of the National Office.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:45.000
And with that job, I got to meet a lot of the local people.

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:50.000
I went to the conferences in the different cities, annual conventions.

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:54.000
I was always there to take the minutes.

00:01:54.000 --> 00:02:00.000
So it was just the pure luck of having the employment office send you to the NAACP?

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:03.000
And the place I think is so good.

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:07.000
I don't know maybe my guardian angels were watching over me.

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:16.000
And that's how I got to meet the secretary of the NAACP, the executive secretary Walter White and Roy Wilkins.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:22.000
I used to call him Pops and he eventually gave me a way of marriage really to third Marshal.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:27.000
He was the legal counsel there.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:32.000
So when you said you were working as secretary of the director of branches, was that Gloster B. Current?

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:34.000
Gloster B. Current, yes.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:41.000
So can you talk about what some of your day-to-day work was like when you were doing that job?

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:51.000
Well, it was mostly correspondence but we got to meet a lot of people coming into the city for help and going to the annual conventions.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:55.000
And that's how they got to know me.

00:02:55.000 --> 00:03:03.000
You know, when Walter White divorces Black wife and married a white woman that practically broke up the whole organization.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:06.000
And so when Thurgood proposed, I said no way.

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:10.000
A lot of people still consider me as a foreigner.

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:14.000
How I wasn't too familiar to people then?

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:22.000
I said no way, no. But he insisted. He said, I'm marrying you. I'm not marrying the country and they're not marrying me.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:24.000
And that's how we got married.

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:25.000
That's interesting.

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:30.000
What was it like to work for the organization when that was happening around Walter White's marriage?

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:40.000
I feel blessed, really, to have been at the organization at that time and learned a lot for myself, really.

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:45.000
And I got to know a lot of the local people in the south especially.

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:53.000
It took us in when we couldn't stay in hotels. We stayed in their private homes and they fed us and treated us like kingsmen.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:04:01.000
They themselves, you know, as Serger said, we were cowards. The lawyers were cowards.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:09.000
Because they'd go into one city, fight their case, argue their case, and take the fastest train and the fastest airplane out.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:18.000
But he says, the local people put their names on the briefs. They stayed there and met daily opposition, hostile people.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:21.000
They're the real heroes in the civil rights fight.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:28.000
Do you remember some of the people that you stayed with? Or, you know, some of the people that you interacted with in the local communities?

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:37.000
A lot of people, I can't remember their names in Atlanta, Georgia, and Chattanooga, Tennessee, and Oklahoma City.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:45.000
I got to meet a lot of them. And they'd got so that they treated me as a daughter.

00:04:45.000 --> 00:05:00.000
I know that there was a lot of hospitality. I've read, I was actually over at the Library of Congress looking at some of the NAACP papers this past week and reading about some of the annual conventions.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:06.000
What were some of the main issues that you remember typing comments on or working on?

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:18.000
Well, I was there for the cases of Groveland Four, Groveland Four that were indicted because they're so-called right-of-white women or four boys.

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:34.000
I remember Emmett Till case in Chicago. And I don't know so many other cases that were involved, because the branches were responsible for taking care of the cases back.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:43.000
They got advice from our office, you know, from the lawyers and from my boss, who was hit of all the branches in the country.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:47.000
So I got to interact with a lot of people.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:54.000
You must have, while you were in there taking notes, heard a lot of discussions of strategy.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:57.000
Yes, yes. Did you? What did you?

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:05.000
As I said, it was a blessing for me to learn about our country, the way it is and what's being done.

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:11.000
And as I look back today, we've come a long way. But we still have ways to go.

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:15.000
What do you think are some of the most important changes?

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:26.000
Well, for instance, going to restaurants, going into hotels, without being looked at and without being turned away.

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:35.000
And in some cases, we couldn't even eat in the restaurants. People fed us. We went to conventions there and they fed us.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:48.000
Believe me, I don't know how they did it. And I remember riding in one car with Thurgood and one of the branch members says,

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:57.000
Judge, open up that dog compartment. He opened up. He says, you see, there's a Bible there and there's a gun there.

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:02.000
He says, we'll use the Bible first. If that doesn't work, we'll use the gun.

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:10.000
That's how they lived. You know, it's remarkable how they did that. I praised them to high.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:22.000
It must have been really exciting to watch those cases come in and see the victories through that period of the 50s and 60s.

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:29.000
Well, I worked in the branch department, so I didn't have anything to do with the little graphics.

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:36.000
But when they ran short of help for this, the Brown v. Board of Education versus Board, they needed a center graphic help.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:45.000
And I was there with, well, we were in the same office anyhow. And all the other cases.

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:55.000
I remember reading about a meeting in Atlanta shortly after the Brown v. Board of Education decision and the excitement and anticipation that things would move really quickly.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:08:00.000
And then, of course, that's not really what happened. Was that hard to see, too? The resistance?

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:08.000
Well, we celebrated for a while, but after a while Thurgood said, I don't know about you, fools, but our work has just begun.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:11.000
He was a realist then.

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:16.000
Do you know when he had that moment where he said that or when he thought that, where in the process it was?

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:22.000
When we were celebrating, I think it was the Brown v. Board of Education or one of the big cases.

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:31.000
As usual, we celebrated at the office, but after about an hour, so that's when he said it.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:36.000
I don't know where he's true, but I'm going back to work or work has just begun.

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:39.000
Well, he certainly was right.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:45.000
You said that you were concerned about getting married because you didn't want to be perceived as...

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:54.000
Well, I didn't want to break the organization up like the other incident took place, but he said no.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:57.000
Well, was the response when you got married?

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:05.000
They all loved me. They all thought of me as their daughter really because they've seen me around the branches, conventions.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:09.000
I was always there taking the minutes, recording the minutes.

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:12.000
So you think it helped the people knew you as a person?

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:15.000
I think it did. I really think so.

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:24.000
Yeah. And not only that working in the branch department, anything that they needed help in the local people would contact the branch department,

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:32.000
the first person they would get to is me, and if I could help them without bothering the director, that's what happened.

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:36.000
And that's how they got to do it. So you were already so bad that they could count on?

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:38.000
Ah, I can't help but...

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:41.000
That was just a nice secret, you know.

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:44.000
Did you get it?

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:50.000
It really has been a lesson for me, myself, and a blessing in a way.

00:09:50.000 --> 00:10:00.000
Having been born and raised in Hawaii, you know, you go to school, you learn all the bad words, all the different languages.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:04.000
Who's this? What do you do, don't you?

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:10.000
It must have been really different, you know, being in Hawaii, where you were with such a mix of people.

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:13.000
And then coming here, where there were so many divisions based on the reason.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:17.000
Right, it was. It was a lesson to me, really.

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:23.000
Were there particular moments where you first experienced that and began to understand the differences?

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:33.000
Well, I remember about a week after the Brown v. Board of Education, the Henderson v. United States, that was a dining room case, where the dining room was segregated, you know, one section.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:40.000
There's a section of dining room there with a wall and a curtain there for the black people.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:49.000
And I remember getting in the train going to Chattanooga about a week after that, with one of the lawyers.

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:54.000
The lawyer always is there to confer with our branches.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:59.000
Well, he was traveling, and I was traveling along the secretary.

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:12.000
And his name was Franklin H. Williams, one of the lawyers who became a first Negro ambassador to Ghana, if I'm not mistaken.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:19.000
But he was the lawyer then, and he said, you know, he could pass for anything.

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:36.000
And he said, hey, it's just about you. You know, he asked my boss, who was pitch black, as a matter of fact, they call him Bubo and you know, he only took it from his close friends especially from there.

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:41.000
I can imagine. And he said, no, no, not me.

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:48.000
He was too soon, and the membership secretary was a woman, said, I'm too tired, I just want to rest.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:53.000
So, Frank said, how about you, says, I said, sure, let's go.

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:56.000
So, you didn't mind traveling, sir?

00:11:56.000 --> 00:12:00.000
I was new then, I didn't know that you don't move.

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:06.000
So, we went to the dining car, and the head waiter looked at Frank, he couldn't figure him out.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:12.000
He looked at me, and he couldn't figure me out with my long hair, flower, my hair.

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:19.000
So, he took us to the table, not, you know, in the partition section, but right next to it.

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:24.000
And Frank looked at him, and he said, poor, call me, you.

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:29.000
And he said, oh, come back this way, and took us to the center of the dining car.

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:39.000
And while we were eating, every time Frank saw the head waiter coming down the aisle, he said, oh, you're there with something in French, and my only French was, we.

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:50.000
And then I went all during the dinner there, but it was quite an experience, because he would look at us, he was still trying to figure out what I was, what he was.

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:52.000
Did you ever feel nervous in those situations?

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:55.000
Never, never.

00:12:55.000 --> 00:13:00.000
Now, eat me, come here from Hawaii, you know.

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:04.000
Did you continue to work at the NAACP after you were married?

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:15.000
No, I stopped working in 55, but I kept in close contact, of course, with Thurgood Marshall still being in law, you were there.

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:25.000
What was it like to start seeing all these major events taking place within the civil rights movement? Do you remember the sit-ins and how you felt when they started?

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:33.000
I remember segregation very well, you couldn't go to a different place, you couldn't sit in any place.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:36.000
I just wish Thurgood Marshall were here.

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:53.000
I just wish to see his work and the work of his lawyers, really, but most of them were gone, like you interviewed Robert L. Carter, Robert L. Carter, one of Thurgood Marshall first assistants there, and Mildred Bond Roxborough Roxborough, she was a few-sector under my boss.

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:54.000
Oh, really?

00:13:54.000 --> 00:14:00.000
My boss was the one that hired all the few secretaries for the branch department, and she was one of them.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:04.000
What was her territory? Where did she travel to?

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:14.000
Well, they tried to travel all over, but they usually go to where they were born and around that area.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:23.000
You said a little bit ago, you're talking about how much has changed, but some things that are still...

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:29.000
You still get nasty looks every once in a while, and you can feel the difference.

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:33.000
They would serve you, but you can feel the difference.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:43.000
I don't know if you've been watching the news, but did you follow the cases that were handed down earlier this week, the Shelby County v. Holder?

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:54.000
Yes, in a way, we've made a lot of progress, but I see the court has gone back to some of the few things that invalidated some of the...

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:56.000
But we're getting there.

00:14:56.000 --> 00:15:04.000
What was it like to move from New York City to Washington, D.C.? I understand it was still somewhat of a Southern town, then.

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:14.000
Well, from one to the other, I guess I got used to moving then, after New York, you know, what else is new?

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:18.000
Did you get involved in the community when you were here in Washington?

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:26.000
Not too much, because with third of being with legal work and with the NAACP, I have to keep distance.

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:32.000
I had to cut out a lot of my friends as a matter of fact because of the cases involved and so forth.

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:36.000
And parties, you know, you have to be careful.

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:39.000
Is that so that it's not perceived as a conflict of interest?

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:41.000
Yes, yes.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:47.000
What was it like then for you to have to sort of, you know, because obviously this has a big impact on your life?

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:52.000
Whew! I don't know where to start.

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:59.000
I just feel blessed to have gone through what I did. I learned a lot.

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:01.000
I learned a lot.

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:10.000
What were some of the cases that seemed most memorable to you, either that Justice Marshall was involved in as an attorney or as a justice?

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:13.000
I think the Brown v. Board of Education case was the most important.

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:18.000
And there's so many on this really.

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:21.000
And at my age, this was in the 50s.

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:26.000
You don't want to pull out these cases and sort of rehash them.

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:32.000
Did your brothers and sisters come follow you to the mainland to New York?

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:37.000
Well, not to work, no, but to stay in it.

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:40.000
John W. Marshall, you remember meeting any of my brothers?

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:46.000
No, as a matter of fact, they're all deceased now except for my one sister.

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:50.000
And she's still in her room. She used to teach there.

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:54.000
Do you get back to Hawaii or did you go back very often?

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:57.000
Not too often. It's too long a trip.

00:16:57.000 --> 00:17:04.000
You know, five hours to the west coast, another five to Hawaii.

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:07.000
And it's so much easier with the telephone now.

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:15.000
You know, a few cents, but I remember making my first cell phone call, I'm going back in 48 or 49.

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:21.000
My very first cell phone call because I couldn't afford it, $35 a week.

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:28.000
Wow. But I said I was promoting, got $50 a week, so called home.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:31.000
And we cried, and we cried.

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:37.000
And I got the view of the phone when we began with so I second time I called home,

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:40.000
talk, cry later.

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:43.000
You're not going to cry, I think you're a mother.

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:45.000
You don't want to cry while you're on.

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:49.000
No, I just cry afterwards.

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:53.000
Can you describe what the National Office of the NAACP was like,

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:56.000
like how it was set up and who you were working with?

00:17:56.000 --> 00:18:00.000
Well, there was a centographic pool where I started off with.

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:06.000
And then there was a branch department that took, over saw the 1500 branches around the country.

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:14.000
And on the other side was the legal department in the forest to help our branches in their legal work.

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:21.000
And upstairs there was Roy Wilkins at Walter White, but it was like a family really.

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:27.000
After work would sit around for a while and go out to dinner, the few of us.

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:34.000
It really got so, you know, we didn't think of anything except brothers and sisters.

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:39.000
Do you think there was more camaraderie because of the work that you were doing?

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:42.000
Because it felt like it didn't work?

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:44.000
Yes.

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:48.000
Are there some of the people, do you, can you?

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:53.000
I was wondering if you would be willing to describe some of the people that you worked with.

00:18:53.000 --> 00:18:57.000
You know, help us get a portrait of people that aren't with us anymore.

00:18:57.000 --> 00:19:01.000
Oh, Walter White.

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:05.000
It was a wonderful administrator.

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:08.000
But sometimes he was above all of us.

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:12.000
It was Roy Wilkins that did the work there.

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:18.000
He was the one that met the people locally more often.

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:22.000
And of course, they're good at my boss.

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:30.000
It was like a family really, just like a family, especially when you went to conferences and conventions.

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:34.000
Do you remember some of the places you went for the conventions?

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:40.000
Atlanta, Oklahoma City.

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:47.000
They see Atlanta, Oklahoma City, where else did I go?

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:53.000
Well, we started off in Boston, actually, that was my first convention in 1950.

00:19:53.000 --> 00:20:03.000
Then to Atlanta, then Oklahoma City, then Chicago, you knew even Dallas Texas.

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:09.000
And it must have been something else to have people coming from all over the country for the conventions.

00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:14.000
And that's how I got to know them because they always had branch problems.

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:18.000
And they would come to my boss and I would be there.

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:26.000
But you have to give them credit really to do what they do in those times.

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:29.000
It's amazing, just amazing.

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:33.000
And the way they treated us, they treated us like kings and queens.

00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:37.000
But they didn't have to.

00:20:37.000 --> 00:20:42.000
Well, I'm sure they appreciated the help.

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:51.000
But somebody they could call on and somebody they could work with, even while they're struggling where they are.

00:20:51.000 --> 00:20:56.000
Especially through our department, actually, the director of branches.

00:20:56.000 --> 00:21:01.000
We had to come through our department for any problems.

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:08.000
And we tried to solve them as much as we can before taking it to the board.

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:10.000
Before taking it to the board?

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:15.000
Board of directors for any conflict that we couldn't solve.

00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:21.000
What are some of the things that you think young people should know about those days?

00:21:21.000 --> 00:21:24.000
That they shouldn't take anything for granted.

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:30.000
It was people in the earlier days that went through all the sacrifices.

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:37.000
They went through all the indignities to build what they are today.

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:43.000
So many people take so many things for granted.

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:46.000
Especially the younger generations.

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:51.000
And you think of the older generations in the south, what they went through.

00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:54.000
They were wonderful people.

00:21:54.000 --> 00:22:01.000
Did you travel much in the south after the Civil Rights Movement, enough to see some of the changes?

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:04.000
Well, up until 1955.

00:22:04.000 --> 00:22:06.000
So you didn't travel after that?

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:07.000
No, no.

00:22:07.000 --> 00:22:10.000
So you never married it.

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:14.000
He kept me busy.

00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:18.000
And my oldest son, of course, was proud of him.

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:22.000
Can you talk about the church here where we are meeting today?

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:31.000
I think having my deep faith in God was what kept us through.

00:22:31.000 --> 00:22:43.000
When you have to have faith in God, you know, you talk to Him in private and just get everything out of the system.

00:22:43.000 --> 00:22:48.000
And that is the way I feel.

00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:55.000
And that allows you to keep a good up and face things?

00:22:55.000 --> 00:22:59.000
Where did you live when you came to New York?

00:22:59.000 --> 00:23:03.000
Where did we leave you on 123rd Street?

00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:06.000
501 way, 123rd.

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:13.000
We were first leave at 409 Edgecombe Avenue, which was supposed to be the high society of the Negro world.

00:23:13.000 --> 00:23:15.000
Then they built a co-op.

00:23:15.000 --> 00:23:21.000
The first co-op, middle income co-op in New York, that was what they call Morningside Gardens.

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:23.000
And it was wonderful.

00:23:23.000 --> 00:23:30.000
We didn't have to go out to part because they all came to us because we had the two young boys and they didn't have any.

00:23:30.000 --> 00:23:32.000
It was easier for them to come.

00:23:32.000 --> 00:23:37.000
Can you describe what that living in that community was like?

00:23:37.000 --> 00:23:39.000
We had so many friends.

00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:48.000
There was Edward R. Dudley, who became ambassador to Liberia the first ever before Franklin H. Williams.

00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:52.000
He lived across the building and there was a doctor there.

00:23:52.000 --> 00:23:56.000
I can't think which was my husband's doctor.

00:23:56.000 --> 00:23:59.000
It's so convenient.

00:23:59.000 --> 00:24:02.000
Robert L. Carter, one of the lawyers lived in another.

00:24:02.000 --> 00:24:05.000
There were five buildings there.

00:24:05.000 --> 00:24:07.000
But we were all within one community.

00:24:07.000 --> 00:24:09.000
We lived in one building.

00:24:09.000 --> 00:24:15.000
We had Richard Parrish, who was the director of the urban league.

00:24:15.000 --> 00:24:19.000
They were above us and we had George Dockery.

00:24:19.000 --> 00:24:22.000
He was a dentist.

00:24:22.000 --> 00:24:32.000
And between George Dockery's wife and Richard Parrish's wife, they tried to buy the boys' attention.

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:39.000
So one would sneak up and leave food at the front door for the boys.

00:24:39.000 --> 00:24:43.000
Then we'd come home again another time and it was food from the yard.

00:24:43.000 --> 00:24:46.000
They would try to outdo one another.

00:24:46.000 --> 00:24:49.000
They were going on.

00:24:49.000 --> 00:24:52.000
They were wonderful, wonderful.

00:24:52.000 --> 00:25:01.000
And Louis Jefferson, who was a great artist, lived there.

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:04.000
So it sounds like it was quite a community.

00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:06.000
It wasn't just a place to live.

00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:08.000
It was. It was wonderful.

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:09.000
That's wonderful.

00:25:09.000 --> 00:25:11.000
I couldn't think of a better place for you.

00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:13.000
And I said, we didn't have to go out.

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:17.000
They came because of the boys and you were always easy for them to come.

00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:27.000
I read in something that after you moved to D.C., at a certain point, you moved out and became the first people to integrate a white community.

00:25:27.000 --> 00:25:34.000
Well, we lived at 64 G Street, which was walking distance to the church.

00:25:34.000 --> 00:25:37.000
I still come to this church here.

00:25:37.000 --> 00:25:42.000
And then it got so that circuit couldn't stand the steps.

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:49.000
But we did move to another co-op on four streets, which was three stories.

00:25:49.000 --> 00:25:54.000
But more steps, and after one year, it's enough.

00:25:54.000 --> 00:25:58.000
And we found a thousand Virginia, which is wonderful.

00:25:58.000 --> 00:26:02.000
Let me see if.

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:05.000
Okay.

00:26:05.000 --> 00:26:07.000
I'll ask you about this.

00:26:07.000 --> 00:26:10.000
They said that you moved to the Lake Barcroft.

00:26:10.000 --> 00:26:11.000
Lake Barcroft.

00:26:11.000 --> 00:26:13.000
That's where we are now.

00:26:13.000 --> 00:26:16.000
Okay. And was that a white community before you moved in?

00:26:16.000 --> 00:26:18.000
It still is, practically.

00:26:18.000 --> 00:26:23.000
Ramsey Clark, who was then Attorney General, lived in Lake Barcroft.

00:26:23.000 --> 00:26:29.000
And he says, boss, you have to come and integrate the place.

00:26:29.000 --> 00:26:32.000
So we moved from Washington to Lake Barcroft.

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:37.000
But as far as I know, we're still the only family there.

00:26:37.000 --> 00:26:40.000
Did you have any trouble when you moved over there?

00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:44.000
No, not really. When we first moved there,

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:48.000
saw a bunch of kids came by and they welcomed our boys.

00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:50.000
Yeah. Yeah.

00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:58.000
So you were the first and still one of the only African-American families.

00:26:58.000 --> 00:27:02.000
And yet there's one Asian family.

00:27:02.000 --> 00:27:04.000
One Asian family?

00:27:04.000 --> 00:27:07.000
Out of 1500. So it's very white.

00:27:07.000 --> 00:27:10.000
Well, it's not advertised, you know.

00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:12.000
That's another reason.

00:27:12.000 --> 00:27:15.000
But people don't move out of Lake Barcroft.

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:17.000
How can you move?

00:27:17.000 --> 00:27:20.000
Beautiful home. The lake is there.

00:27:20.000 --> 00:27:23.000
Walking distance to the bus.

00:27:23.000 --> 00:27:26.000
So it's a lovely location.

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:28.000
Yeah, it is.

00:27:28.000 --> 00:27:30.000
Yeah.

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:35.000
There were a list here of some organizations that you were involved in.

00:27:35.000 --> 00:27:39.000
I'm told you were involved in the National Capitol Auxiliary.

00:27:39.000 --> 00:27:43.000
That's the largest wives.

00:27:43.000 --> 00:27:44.000
Okay.

00:27:44.000 --> 00:27:53.000
That's a wise up from the district, Maryland, Virginia.

00:27:53.000 --> 00:27:56.000
And what kinds of things do you do?

00:27:56.000 --> 00:28:01.000
Well, we usually have meetings get together and conscious.

00:28:01.000 --> 00:28:02.000
Yeah.

00:28:02.000 --> 00:28:06.000
And they honor a Supreme Court wives every year.

00:28:06.000 --> 00:28:07.000
Yeah.

00:28:07.000 --> 00:28:08.000
So is it?

00:28:08.000 --> 00:28:10.000
Then I have the Travelers Aid.

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:16.000
I used to be on the board of Travelers Aid and Board of the Legal Defense Fund.

00:28:16.000 --> 00:28:17.000
Yeah.

00:28:17.000 --> 00:28:19.000
What do you do as part of those boards?

00:28:19.000 --> 00:28:21.000
As part of what?

00:28:21.000 --> 00:28:26.000
So when you're on the board of the legal fund and the LASVP legal fund,

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:28.000
what kind of work do you do with that?

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:36.000
Well, we decide on policies, you know, and what cases we should go into and recommend and things like that.

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:37.000
Is that difficult?

00:28:37.000 --> 00:28:38.000
Not really.

00:28:38.000 --> 00:28:39.000
Yeah.

00:28:39.000 --> 00:28:40.000
Not really.

00:28:40.000 --> 00:28:45.000
Are there cases that are memorable to you that you were involved in deciding to go for a role?

00:28:45.000 --> 00:28:50.000
Well, really Brown v. Board of Education is the one that we stand out.

00:28:50.000 --> 00:28:57.000
So are there things that you can think are important for people to know about your life and about the work and things you've been involved in?

00:28:57.000 --> 00:29:00.000
I'm just an ordinary person.

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:01.000
I know this is...

00:29:01.000 --> 00:29:10.000
I know that I'm blessed to have gone through what I did, you know, and in those times, and coming from a wall is especially.

00:29:10.000 --> 00:29:11.000
Yeah.

00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:18.000
There's a quote in one of the history books that I like and it talks about ordinary people doing extraordinary things.

00:29:18.000 --> 00:29:22.000
And I think that there's a lot of that in the civil rights movement.

00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:27.000
I'm only an ordinary person doing ordinary things.

00:29:27.000 --> 00:29:29.000
Very, very modest.

00:29:29.000 --> 00:29:33.000
You know, I just feel best and you do what you have to do.

00:29:33.000 --> 00:29:41.000
You raise your family and with Thurgood being away a lot, I made it a point to stay home with their children, you know.

00:29:41.000 --> 00:29:44.000
Well, thank you very much for being with us.

00:29:44.000 --> 00:29:49.000
I know that it's a challenge and that you are eager to get home.

00:29:49.000 --> 00:29:52.000
Well, I don't mind it.

00:29:52.000 --> 00:29:56.000
I just want to say it's been a blessing.

00:29:56.000 --> 00:29:59.000
I think I live a charm life.

00:29:59.000 --> 00:30:04.000
Of course, after putting up with John W. Marshall, I want to start.

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:06.000
John W. Marshall doesn't get to be there.

00:30:06.000 --> 00:30:08.000
He's a wonderful movie.

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:10.000
John W. Marshall doesn't see them 55 years old.

00:30:10.000 --> 00:30:12.000
Oh my god.

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:14.000
John W. Marshall, you're going to speak up?

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:16.000
I'm a younger.

00:30:16.000 --> 00:30:18.000
A younger of a year.

00:30:18.000 --> 00:30:21.000
Yeah, the younger of my old, no, the son is 57.

00:30:21.000 --> 00:30:22.000
Yeah.

00:30:22.000 --> 00:30:24.000
Can you imagine?

00:30:24.000 --> 00:30:25.000
Can you imagine?

00:30:25.000 --> 00:30:31.000
I was going to say that must be an interesting way to know your age if I'm watching your children.

00:30:31.000 --> 00:30:34.000
Well, it's been a challenge.

00:30:34.000 --> 00:30:37.000
No, but it's been wonderful, really.

00:30:37.000 --> 00:30:38.000
Yeah.

00:30:38.000 --> 00:30:40.000
Well, thank you very much.

00:30:40.000 --> 00:30:41.000
You're welcome.

00:30:41.000 --> 00:30:44.000
Unless you want to ask my son.

00:30:44.000 --> 00:30:46.000
He said all.

00:30:46.000 --> 00:30:55.000
He was well to begin with Marshall and then became the director of the United States Marshals Service.

00:30:55.000 --> 00:30:59.000
And he's now with the Transportation Department.

00:30:59.000 --> 00:31:08.000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.
